title: Founder, CEO
summary: I am a dyslexic physicist, data scientist, and serial entrepreneur. I am currently building Vnote.ai, a voice-writing application that has its own Large Language Model for asking questions.How did I get here? When I sold my first company, I became a Vice President in a 20,000-person organization. I spent much of my time asking questions to help people clarify their ideas. I took my role seriously. I got an executive coach and enrolled in executive coaching lessons. I worked to support for my talented team.  Still, I discovered that being a good manager is not enough. Feedback in the form of a question (not an answer) can have a transformative effect, but it has to come at the right time. I often do my best thinking when I am away from my keyboard. My brain loads itself with information when I interact with people or computers, then I synthesize the essential parts when I step away. This is why I wanted a voice-writing tool that I could use when walking. The need for clear writing as only increased in the post-pandemic world.In 2023, I became public about my dyslexia, a neurological difference that makes it easier for me to speak than to read or write. Research shows that dyslxia also leads to more interconnected, rather than linear, ideas. I have connected with 100s of dyslexics worldwide and am excited about helping non-traditional thinkers get great results with their written words.You can check out what I'm building for free at: https://vnote.ai/I also occasionally write about my journey on substack: https://koshnick.substack.com/
titleDescription: Voice-writing app with a custom question-asking model.https://vnote.ai/
name: Nick Koshnick

title: Founder
summary: Janos Dobronszki is a seasoned full-stack software engineer with over 20 years of experience, beginning his programming career before the internet was even a household staple.He has been part of startups with over $700 million in investments, with deep expertise in microservices, distributed computing, Golang, Angular, Typescript, and DevOps. Janos has a passion for product design and innovation, always pushing the boundaries of what's possible in software engineering.Despite being a non-native English speaker, Janos's writing has made a mark in the tech community. An article he penned about Go in 2014 remains a reference on Wikipedia (search for Dobronszki at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Go_(programming_language)). Beyond his professional work, Janos enjoys mentoring junior engineers and has successfully guided several into thriving careers.Janos is the founder of Singulatron, a self-hosted AI development platform.
